f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bitget calculates funding rates based on the premium/discount between the perpetual contract price and the underlying ETH spot price, with payments occurring at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. The funding rate is determined by the 8-hour time-weighted average premium and interest rate component. Long positions pay short positions when funding rates are positive, while short positions pay longs when rates turn negative. Bitget caps funding rates at ±2.5% per 8-hour period to prevent extreme market conditions."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ETH","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT on Bitget consistently ranks among the top 3 ETH perpetual contracts globally by volume, ensuring minimal slippage for large arbitrage positions. The pair's mega-volume status and ETH's volatility create frequent funding rate inefficiencies between Bitget and other major exchanges. Bitget's competitive maker fees of 0.02% enhance profitability for delta-neutral funding strategies."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT funding rates on Bitget typically range from -0.1% to +0.3% per 8-hour period, with extreme readings reaching ±1% during high volatility events. During bullish periods, funding rates consistently trend positive as retail traders favor long positions, creating profitable opportunities for short-side arbitrage. The pair shows predictable patterns around major ETH network upgrades and DeFi protocol launches when speculative interest peaks. Weekend periods often exhibit lower absolute funding rates due to reduced institutional activity, while Tuesday-Thursday sessions show the highest rate volatility."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between Bitget and Binance or OKX frequently yields 0.05-0.15% profit per 8-hour cycle when funding rate differentials exceed 0.2%. Bitget's fast order execution and deep orderbook allow for efficient delta-neutral position establishment using spot ETH hedging. The exchange's copy trading ecosystem can amplify funding rate movements as popular traders open large directional positions that retail followers replicate. Market makers should monitor Bitget's funding rate predictions 2-4 hours before settlement to capture the most profitable entry points."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Management"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Bitget's relatively shorter operational history compared to Binance or OKX requires careful counterparty risk assessment for large arbitrage positions. The exchange's growing but still developing institutional infrastructure may result in occasional API delays during high-volatility periods that could impact funding arbitrage timing. Traders should maintain position sizes under 5% of total orderbook depth to ensure smooth exit execution and avoid contributing to funding rate distortions. ETH's high volatility demands tight delta hedging with spot positions to prevent directional exposure from overwhelming funding profits."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are typical ETH/USDT funding rates on Bitget?","answer":"ETH/USDT funding rates on Bitget typically range from -0.1% to +0.3% per 8-hour period under normal market conditions. During high volatility or strong directional moves, rates can reach ±1% as trader sentiment becomes extremely one-sided."},{"question":"How does Bitget's funding calculation compare to other exchanges?","answer":"Bitget uses a similar funding rate methodology to major exchanges, calculating rates based on the 8-hour time-weighted average premium plus interest rate component. However, Bitget's newer user base tends to be more retail-oriented, often creating higher absolute funding rates than institutional-heavy platforms."},{"question":"What's the minimum position size for profitable ETH funding arbitrage on Bitget?","answer":"Given Bitget's 0.02% maker fees, minimum position sizes of $10,000-$25,000 are typically needed to generate meaningful profits after fees. Smaller positions may be profitable during extreme funding rate periods above ±0.5% per cycle."},{"question":"How reliable is Bitget's ETH/USDT contract for funding strategies?","answer":"Bitget's ETH/USDT contract offers excellent liquidity and reliable funding payments, though traders should monitor API performance during volatile periods. The exchange's growing institutional adoption and improved infrastructure make it increasingly suitable for professional arbitrage strategies."}]}]
